<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1945-06-20T10:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1945-06-20T10:00:00-05:00" n="912" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d912">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 P.W./6–2045: Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Harriman</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-06-20T18:00:00+03:00">June 20,
                                    1945—6 p.m.</date>
                                <lb/> [Received 8:30 p.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>2187. Emb’s 2135, June 17.<note n="15" xml:id="d912fn1">Not
                                printed.</note> Supporting our notification to Soviet Govt that Amer
                            Govt was informing Italian Govt it would welcome Italian declaration of
                            war on Japan British Amb<note n="16" xml:id="d912fn2">Sir Archibald
                                Clark Kerr.</note> on June 17 wrote Molotov<note n="17" xml:id="d912fn3">Vyaeheslav Mikhailovich Molotov, People’s Commissar
                                for Foreign Affairs of the Soviet Union.</note> that his Govt agreed
                            with proposed American action. Clark Kerr added that British had reed no
                            communication from Italians on subject and did not intend to raise
                            question with them. <pb facs="0974" n="962" xml:id="pg_962"/> British
                            Ambassador Rome<note n="18" xml:id="d912fn4">Sir Noel Charles.</note>
                            instructed to say, if queried by Italians, that British were consulted
                            by Americans and agreed to American proposed action.</p>
                        <p>Rptd London 307, Rome 49.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Harriman</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>